Depending on the methods used for regeneration of adsorbents after each adsorption cycle in a CO2 capture process, several processes can be adopted to achieve CO2 separation, including (1) vacuum and pressure swing adsorption (VSA and PSA), (2) temperature swing adsorption (TSA), (3) electric swing adsorption (ESA), (4) simulated moving bed (SMB), (5) purge displacement (

                           Fig. 1


                        ) 
                        [39] and (6) Electric/magnetic induction swing adsorption (ESA/MISA) ( 

                           Fig. 4

                        ). In addition to these parameters, economic and technical factors must also be considered during the selection of an adsorption method. Choosing the best adsorption method for purification is thus a significant challenge [40].

Direct Air capture Ambient air contains only 400 ppm CO₂, necessitating high binding (−50 to −80 kJ/mol) and chemisorption for effective absorption. TVSA is typically used for regeneration at temperatures below 120 °C and pressures between 0.1-0.3 bars. Mg₂(dobpdc) with appended amines is a promising solid sorbent for DAC due to its strong CO₂ binding (isosteric heats in the range of -50 to -90 kJ/mol) and step-shaped isotherms, allowing for significant uptake even at atmospheric CO₂ partial pressures. Tetraamine-functionalized Mg₂(dobpdc) has 1.7 mmol/g capacity at 400 ppm and 50% RH, with a reduced energy cost of 4.5 MJ/kg CO₂ compared to amine-based DAC systems [166]. The decision tree provides a systematic framework for selecting appropriate processes to achieve efficient CO₂ capture in post-combustion and DAC systems (

   Fig. 5


).
